<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="87" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Measurements</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Male body length 2.90-3.21, width (across suture between meso- and metanotum) 1.07-1.21; female body length 3.30-3.91, width 1.44-1.52. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Color</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Ground color of body pale yellow with extensive black and silvery markings dorsally, legs largely pale yellow (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Telmatometropsis fredyi gen. nov, sp. nov., male A dorsal view B-D Scanning electron micrographs B dorsal view C head, pronotum and anterior portion of mesonotum, dorsal view D apex of thorax and base of abdomen, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 400 μm (B); 100 μm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.58548.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554394" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">1A</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">
<taxonomicName genus="Structural" lsidName="Structural characteristics" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" rank="species" species="characteristics">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Structural characteristics</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Eyes elongate, with a pair of long ocular setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Telmatometropsis fredyi gen. nov, sp. nov., male A dorsal view B-D Scanning electron micrographs B dorsal view C head, pronotum and anterior portion of mesonotum, dorsal view D apex of thorax and base of abdomen, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 400 μm (B); 100 μm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.58548.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554394" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">1B</figureCitation>
). Head with four pairs of trichobothria (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Telmatometropsis fredyi gen. nov, sp. nov., male A dorsal view B-D Scanning electron micrographs B dorsal view C head, pronotum and anterior portion of mesonotum, dorsal view D apex of thorax and base of abdomen, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 400 μm (B); 100 μm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.58548.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554394" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">1C</figureCitation>
). Antenna shorter than body length; antennomere I thickest, curved laterally at base, longer than antennomere II; antennomere II shortest, thicker than antennomeres III and IV; antennomere III longer than antennomere I; antennomere IV longest (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Telmatometropsis fredyi gen. nov, sp. nov., male A dorsal view B-D Scanning electron micrographs B dorsal view C head, pronotum and anterior portion of mesonotum, dorsal view D apex of thorax and base of abdomen, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 400 μm (B); 100 μm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.58548.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554394" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">1A, B</figureCitation>
). Labium long, extending to mesosternum. Pronotum short, trapezoid (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Telmatometropsis fredyi gen. nov, sp. nov., male A dorsal view B-D Scanning electron micrographs B dorsal view C head, pronotum and anterior portion of mesonotum, dorsal view D apex of thorax and base of abdomen, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 400 μm (B); 100 μm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.58548.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554394" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">1C</figureCitation>
). Mesonotum about three times as long as pronotum, posterior margin slightly concave (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Telmatometropsis fredyi gen. nov, sp. nov., male A dorsal view B-D Scanning electron micrographs B dorsal view C head, pronotum and anterior portion of mesonotum, dorsal view D apex of thorax and base of abdomen, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 400 μm (B); 100 μm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.58548.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554394" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">1A, B</figureCitation>
). Fore femur subequal in length to fore tibia, slightly curved at the base in dorsal view; fore tibia with apicolateral row of short, distinctive setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Telmatometropsis fredyi gen. nov, sp. nov., male, scanning electron micrographs A fore leg, ventral view B-E fore tarsus B external lateral view C internal lateral view D dorsal view E ventral view. Scale bars: 200 μm (A); 300 μm (B); 20 μm (C); 60 μm (D); 40 μm (E)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.58548.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554396" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">3A</figureCitation>
); fore tarsus covered with short yellow setae; fore tarsomere I about one third the length of fore tarsomere II; male fore tarsomere II strongly curved in lateral view, flattened laterally, apically bifid with a shorter and a longer portion; claws directed mesally (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Telmatometropsis fredyi gen. nov, sp. nov., male, scanning electron micrographs A fore leg, ventral view B-E fore tarsus B external lateral view C internal lateral view D dorsal view E ventral view. Scale bars: 200 μm (A); 300 μm (B); 20 μm (C); 60 μm (D); 40 μm (E)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.58548.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554396" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">3A-E</figureCitation>
). Mid femur about two-thirds the length of mid tibia; mid tibia less than twice the length of mid tarsus, about as long as medial length of body from anterior margin of pronotum to apex of abdomen, occasionally almost as long as body; mid tarsus shorter than mid femur, article I subequal to article II or a little longer. Hind femur longer than mid femur; hind tibia about two-thirds the length of hind femur, densely covered with setae; hind tarsus about half the length of hind tibia, article I longer than article II.
</paragraph>
